# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: barreiros-manufacturer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] Abadal was born on 27 July 1875 in Manresa and by the end of the century was a notable cyclist in Barcelona.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] His first motor vehicle was a 1.75-hp Clément tricycle which he raced.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] In 1902 Abadal began selling cars, motorbikes, cycles and accessories from the Auto-Garage Central in Barcelona.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] He won a won a couple of hill climbs at Rabassade near Barcelona.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] The first in February 1904 was in a Clement 16 hp and the second in January 1905 was in a Hispano-Suiza T20.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] Also in 1905, he sold a Hispano-Suiza to King Alfonso XIII.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] His business grew and by 1908 he had branches in Calle Sepúlveda, Plaza Letamendi and Carretera de Sarriá.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] In In October 1912 Abadal married Mercedes Durán, daughter of the wealthy Catalan businessman and industrialist, Joaquim Durán Albert.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] In 1913 Hispano-Suiza cancelled its contract with Abadal so he decided to make his own vehicles under the make Abadal.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] Soon after the inception of the Abadal line in 1913 Abadal visited the Belgian company Impéria.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] They negotiated an agreement whereby Impéria began building Abadals under license as Impéria-Abadal, With the outbreak of World War One and the invasion of Belgium by Germany this arrangement came to a temporary end.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] In 1916 Abadal acquired the Buick agency, and Barcelona-built Abadals after that year had Buick power units and featured custom coachwork.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] In 1919 M A Van Roggen (formerly of Springuel) took over Impéria and built around 170 more Impéria-Abadals.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] Among the models produced were a 2992cc 16-valve four-cylinder OHC sports model and three prototype 5630 cc straight-eights.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] The first models were released simultaneously in 1913 under the direction of Francisco.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] "Abadal 18HP" and "Abadal 25HP" had a four-cylinder engine with a volume of 3.6 liters with a piston stroke of 180 millimeters and a cylinder diameter of 80 millimeters, as well as a four-speed manual gearbox.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] The five-seater open-top car was equipped with a suspension on semi-elliptical springs and traditional at that time drum brakes.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] The models were assembled on a spar frame and generally had technical similarities with other similar cars of that time, in particular with "Hispano-Suiza", but differed in design, for example, a wedge-shaped radiator.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] The maximum speed that the cars could reach was 112 kilometers per hour.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] A 1914 version of the 25HP is held at the Caramulo Museum in Portugal.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] Abadal 45HP had all the same characteristics, but unlike the previous models, it stood out with a six-cylinder engine.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] These cars were more reliable than their predecessors.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] The model was first presented at the Paris Motor Show in 1913.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] Despite the classic appearance of the cars of that time, the "Abadal 15.9HP" was a new racing model of the company and differed from other sports models by its completely wooden body, which was designed and recreated by the French coachbuilder Jean Henri-Labourdette.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] Buick engines had been used under licence in Abadal's since 1916.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] The first cooperative car of the two company's was released in 1923 under a joint name.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] The rear-wheel drive roadster was equipped with a six-cylinder engine with 60 horsepower, which contributed to acceleration of 140 kilometers per hour.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] The car was intended for track racing and weighed 1030 kilograms.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] One of these is held at Collecio D'automobils Salvador Claret near Barcelona.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] There is a note of a Abadal Buick driven by José Rubio Márques winning a hillclimb at Reina near Malaga.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] This was followed by Pascual Sogas winning a hillclimb at Ordal near Barcelona on 29 December 1918 and again at Perdeces near Madrid on 7 June 1919.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] These are likely Buick engined Abadal's as the joint name did not appear till later.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] A Abadal-Buick driven by Leon Derny won a hillclimb at Porta-Coeli near Valencia on 23 June 1923.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] Another racing car rolled off the assembly line in 1921 under another joint name, "Abadal Imperial".
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] This was the last joint project, developed in the year the partnership agreement expired.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] The model turned out to be the fastest version of all those previously released in alliance with "Impéria".
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] It had an 8-cylinder engine with a total volume of 5.6 liters and was capable of accelerating to a maximum speed of 145 kilometers per hour.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] On 12 August 1922 this car won the 40 lap (about 603 km) *Le Grand Prix pour voitures de tourisme* at Spa-Francorchamps.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] It was driven by Baron Raymond de Tornaco and Barthélémy.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] The last car of this brand was a prototype of a luxury sedan with a 3.5-liter engine from the German company Continental AG, on which Francisco had placed great hopes, but they were not destined to come true, because nothing followed beyond the idea and the initial sample.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] The company ceased automobile production in 1923.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] Abadal became an agent of General Motors in Spain.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] General Motors' plans in 1930 related to a prototype named the Abadal Continental never materialised.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] Abadal also produced the Abadal Y-12 aero-engine, a multiple bank in-line engine with twelve cylinders in three banks of four arranged in a Y.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] It was produced during World War One as an experimental aircraft engine.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/abadal] An Abadal featured on a 1977 Spanish postage stamp and a 1984 postage stamp from Nicaragua.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adanero] Adanero was granted the privilege of town (*villa*) in 1630, during the reign of Philip IV, becoming independent from the land of Ávila.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] When Spain was still an autocratic regime, he was appointed prime minister by King Juan Carlos in 1976.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] At the time of his appointment, he was not a well-known figure, making many political forces skeptical of his government.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] However, he oversaw the end of the Francoist Cortes, and the legalisation of all political parties (including the Communist Party of Spain, a particularly difficult move).
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] He led the Union of the Democratic Centre and won the 1977 general election.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] In 1981, he resigned and founded the party Democratic and Social Centre (CDS), which was elected to the Cortes numerous times.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] He retired from politics in 1991 and from public life in 2003, due to Alzheimer's disease.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Adolfo Suárez González was born on 25 September 1932 in Cebreros in the Province of Ávila of Spain, the eldest son of Hipólito Suárez Guerra, a lawyer, and Herminia González Prados.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Both of his parents supported the Republicans during the Spanish Civil War.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] At the age of 18, Suárez was president of the Ávila chapter of Catholic Action.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] He studied law at the University of Salamanca, after which he took a job at the municipal government of Ávila in 1955.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] He subsequently became a member of Opus Dei, and obtained a doctorate at the Central University of Madrid.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] He also worked briefly as a porter at Madrid's Atocha railway station.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] In 1958, Suárez became the personal secretary of Fernando Herrero Tejedor, the newly appointed civil governor of Ávila.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] When Tejedor was made deputy secretary-general of the *Movimiento Nacional* in 1961, Suárez became his *chef de cabinet*.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] He gradually rose through the ranks of the *Movimiento*.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] In 1965, Suárez was appointed programme director of the state broadcaster Radio y Televisión Española (RTVE).
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] In 1967, he was elected to the Francoist Cortes.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] In 1968, Suárez was promoted to civil governor and provincial head of the *Movimiento* in Segovia.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] In 1969, he was made director general of RTVE.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Under this capacity, he became a close friend to future king Prince Juan Carlos.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] In March 1975, Herrero Tejedor became secretary-general of the *Movimiento* while Suárez was appointed deputy secretary-general.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Herrero Tejedor was considered a likely candidate for prime minister until his death in a car accident in June.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] In December, shortly after Francisco Franco's death, Suárez was promoted to secretary-general by prime minister Carlos Arias Navarro, and became a member of Arias's cabinet.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] In the same year, he also became a founding member of the Spanish People's Union (*Unión del Pueblo Español*, UDPE).
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] In July 1976, King Juan Carlos requested the resignation of Arias.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] The relatively obscure Suárez was chosen as the new Prime Minister of Spain, surprising many observers.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] At the age of 43, he was Spain's youngest prime minister in the 20th century.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Due to his Francoist ties, Suárez enjoyed the trust of the political right, while the reformists were dismayed by his appointment.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Nevertheless, it was noted that due to his age (he turned 7 years old the year that the civil war ended), Suárez was not as strongly associated with the bloody Civil War or the most brutal years of Franco's rule as the older politicians.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Within a year of his appointment, Suárez had rapidly introduced reform measures and taken decisive steps in Spain's transition to democracy (*La Transición*).
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] The Political Reform Act, which permitted universal suffrage and established the basis for a new, bicameral parliament, was passed by a huge majority in the Francoist Cortes in November 1976 and overwhelmingly approved by a referendum in December.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Suárez managed to placate the conservative military officers, while also reaching out to Felipe González's Spanish Socialist Workers' Party (PSOE) and later, Santiago Carrillo's Communist Party of Spain (PCE).
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Between February and April 1977, the PSOE and the PCE were both legalised, trade unions were recognised, and the *Movimiento* was abolished.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] The legalisation of the PCE in particular provoked fury in the Spanish military; Suárez responded by sacking hardliners and promoting more liberal officers such as Manuel Gutiérrez Mellado.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] On 15 June, Suárez led the Union of the Democratic Centre (*Unión de Centro Democrático*, UCD) to victory in Spain's first free elections in 41 years, and became the first democratically elected prime minister of the post-Francoist Spain.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] In 1978, during Suárez's premiership, Spain voted in the United Nations General Assembly condemning human rights abuses in Chile, thus distancing Spain from the Francoist-influenced military dictatorship of Augusto Pinochet.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Suárez's centrist government instituted further democratic reforms.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] A new constitution, which recognised Spain as a constitutional monarchy, was approved by a referendum in December 1978.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] In an effort to address separatist tensions and calls for increased local autonomy, Suárez also negotiated the creation of Spain's autonomous communities.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Suárez's coalition won the 1979 Spanish general election under the new constitution.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Suárez's political power eroded as he struggled to deal with economic recession, mounting violent activity by ETA, calls for further regional autonomy and divisions within his own party.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] He became increasingly withdrawn from governance, partly due to a chronic dental condition.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] He survived a motion of no confidence presented by Felipe González and the PSOE in May 1980.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] In January 1981, trailing in the polls behind the PSOE and faced with a revolt within the UCD, Suárez announced his resignation as prime minister.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] A month later, as parliament took the vote to confirm Suárez's successor Leopoldo Calvo-Sotelo, Lieutenant-Colonel Antonio Tejero and around 200 Civil Guards stormed the chamber in an attempted coup and held the lawmakers hostage for some 22 hours.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Suárez, along with two other parliamentarians, exhibited defiance by remaining calmly seated during the panic.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] The 23-F coup attempt ("El Tejerazo") failed as it was opposed by Spain's main newspaper El País (who managed to get a special edition in favor of the constitution issued and distributed on the evening of the coup attempt) and denounced by King Juan Carlos I in a televised address.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Meanwhile, promised military support for the coup failed to materialise – with few exceptions, most notably Jaime Milans del Bosch who led pro-coup troops in Valencia.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] He retired from active politics in 1991, for personal reasons.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Suárez was awarded the *Príncipe de Asturias a la Concordia* in September 1996 for his role in Spain's early democracy.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] On 8 June 2007, during the celebration of the 30th anniversary of the first democratic elections, King Juan Carlos appointed Suárez the 1,193rd Knight of the Order of the Golden Fleece.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] He was also a member of the Club de Madrid, an independent organization (based in Madrid) that is composed of more than 80 former democratic Prime Ministers and Presidents.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] The group works to strengthen democratic governance and leadership.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] On 31 May 2005, Suárez's son, Adolfo Suárez Illana, announced on Spanish television that his father was suffering from Alzheimer's disease.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] The announcement followed speculation about Suárez's health in the Spanish media.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] On 21 March 2014, his son announced that his death from neurological deterioration was imminent.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Suárez then died as a result of a respiratory infection on 23 March 2014 in a clinic in Madrid.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Suarez was given a state funeral and was buried in the cloister of Ávila Cathedral.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] On 26 March 2014, the Spanish government decided to rename the Madrid-Barajas Airport to Adolfo Suárez Madrid–Barajas Airport in honour of his service to the country.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] In December 2025 a woman accused Suárez of sexual abuse between 1982–1985, beginning when she was seventeen and still a minor, and Suárez was about fifty.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] However, no criminal proceedings are expected to take place due to Suárez's death in 2014 and an expiration of the alleged crimes.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Suárez's secretary reportedly disputed the accusations made against her former employer.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Suárez married María del Amparo Illana Elórtegui in 1961.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Their eldest daughter, María del Amparo ("Mariam") Suárez Illana (1962–2004), died of breast cancer on 6 March 2004, following an 11-year illness.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Both of her younger sisters also suffered from the same illness.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] She was the mother of two children, Alejandra Romero Suárez (born 1990), herself the current holder of her grandfather's dukedom, and Fernando Romero Suárez (born 1993).
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Suarez' youngest daughter, María Sonsoles Suárez Illana (born 1967), became a TV news anchor for Antena 3.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] From 1992 to 1994 she was married to José María Martínez-Bordiú y Bassó de Roviralta (a nephew of Cristóbal Martínez-Bordiú, the son-in-law of Francisco Franco); the couple was without issue.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] In 2012 she married the Mozambican musician Paulo Wilson, and they separated in 2017.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Suárez's eldest son, Adolfo Suárez Illana, is a politician and lawyer who is heavily involved with the world of bullfighting; he has two sons.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/adolfo-suárez] Suárez had two more children, his daughter Laura and his son Francisco Javier; both remain unmarried.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The London General Omnibus Company (LGOC) was founded in 1855 to amalgamate and regulate the horse-drawn omnibus services then operating in London.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The company began producing motor omnibuses for its own use in 1909 with the X-type designed by its chief motor engineer, Frank Searle, at works in Blackhorse Lane, Walthamstow.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The X-type was followed by Searle's B-type design, considered to be one of the first mass-produced commercial vehicles.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] In 1912, LGOC was taken over by the Underground Group of companies, which at that time owned most of the London Underground, and extensive tram operations.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] As part of the reorganisation following the takeover, a separate concern was set up for the bus manufacturing elements, and was named Associated Equipment Company, better-known as AEC.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] AEC's first commercial vehicle was a lorry based on the X-type bus chassis.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] With the outbreak of World War I in 1914, AEC's ability to produce large numbers of vehicles using moving-track assembly lines, based on American principles, became important in supplying the increasing need for army lorries.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] AEC commenced large-scale production of their 3-ton Y-type lorry in 1916, including some with Daimler-built engines, badged and supplied as Daimler.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] Continued beyond the end of the war, over 10,000 Y-type lorries were manufactured – making AEC Britain's largest domestic provider of lorries for the nation's military.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] From then on, AEC became associated with both lorries and buses.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] In 1926, AEC and Daimler formed the Associated Daimler Company, which was dissolved two years later.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] In 1927, AEC moved its manufacturing from Walthamstow to a new plant at Southall.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] Rackham was appointed Chief Engineer and Designer in 1928.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] He had previously worked for Leyland Motors.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] His ideas contributed significantly to AEC's reputation for quality and reliability.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] From 1929, AEC produced new models: the names of lorries began with "M" (Majestic, Mammoth, Mercury, and so on), and those of buses began with "R" (Regent, Regal, Renown, and so on).
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] These original "M-models" continued in production until the end of World War II.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] AEC introduced diesel engines across the range in the mid-1930s.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] From 1931 to 1938, AEC and English Electric co-produced trolleybuses.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] AEC supplied the chassis, and English Electric the electric motors and control equipment.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] In 1932, AEC took a controlling interest in the British subsidiary of the American Four Wheel Drive (FWD) company, and began to use more standard AEC components in those vehicles, including the AEC 850 artillery tractor.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] To avoid confusion, these were marketed under the name *Hardy*.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] In 1933, AEC collaborated with the GWR to produce a diesel powered railcar with an art deco styled body.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] This followed on from the successful adaptation of a Regal single-decker bus for rail use.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] Three more were ordered in 1934, the latter fitted with two sets of engines and transmissions.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] A further series fitted with a more angular body were supplied in the years leading up to the war.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] Non-military production stopped in 1941.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] From then until 1944, AEC produced nearly 10,000 vehicles for the war effort.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] During the war, AEC produced their 10-ton 4x4 Matador artillery tractor (an adaptation of their commercial 4x2 Matador lorry that exploited AEC's experience with the Hardy FWD venture).
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The Matador was used for towing guns such as the 5.5-inch medium gun and the 3.7-inch AA gun.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The Matador chassis was used as the basis for the Deacon a self-propelled 6-pounder anti-tank gun, which was used briefly in North Africa.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] A 6x6 version was designated as the "AEC Marshall" but almost always called the Matador.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] Four hundred AEC armoured command vehicles, popularly known as the "Dorchester" (after the hotel), were built on the Matador and Marshall chassis.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] Production of the AEC armoured car started in 1941.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] Three marks were built, with guns from 40 mm to 75 mm, totalling 629 vehicles.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] In 1946, AEC and Leyland Motors formed British United Traction as a joint venture to manufacture trolleybuses and traction equipment for diesel railcars since reduced demand would not require the existing capacity of both parents.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] In 1946, AEC resumed civilian production with the 0661/20 Regent II and the 0662/20 Regal I.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] These were not new models but a recommencement of the most basic AEC 1939 specification bus models.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The single-decker was going to be marketed as Regal II until somebody at Southall remembered the 1936-8 lightweight 0862 model of that name and as a result the name was corrected after the launch publicity had been printed.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] At the end of 1946, the postwar 0961 RT was in build, and by 1948 Mammoth Major, Matador and Monarch Mk IIIs were in production, followed by the 'provincial' Regent III and the Regal III.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] Also in 1948, AEC acquired Crossley Motors and the Maudslay Motor Company and on 1 October 1948 AEC set up Associated Commercial Vehicles (ACV) as the holding company for the newly acquired businesses and its own manufacturing firm, which was renamed AEC Limited.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The initials AEC remained on its vehicles, with the exception of some badge-engineered versions, such as the Crossley Regent bus.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] In 1949, ACV acquired the bus coachbuilding company Park Royal Vehicles, along with its subsidiary Charles H Roe.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] Park Royal designed a new cab for the AEC Mercury in the mid-1950s, which appeared on all models across the range about this time.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The Thornycroft name disappeared from all the vehicles except the specialist airport crash tenders, such as the Nubian, and the Antar off-road tractor unit.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] Production of the AEC Dumptruk was transferred to Basingstoke, and the Thornycroft six-speed constant-mesh gearbox and later nine and ten-speed range-change versions were fitted to AEC, Albion and Leyland buses and lorries.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The AEC engines were used in Finnish Vanaja lorries and buses in the 1960s.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] AEC lorries were given the same "Ergomatic" cabs used across several Leyland marques (including Albion).
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] In 1968, all AEC double-decker buses ceased production with the completion of the last Routemasters, and its last buses, motorcoaches and lorries were built in 1979.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The AEC name actually disappeared from commercial vehicles in 1977, but the Leyland Marathon was built at the Southall plant until British Leyland closed it in 1979.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] In 1979, the production of Leyland (AEC) vehicles was transferred to remaining Leyland Truck and Bus plants.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] ACLOs were principally found in Argentina, Brazil, and particularly in Uruguay, where there were two ACLO fleets (150 buses in total) built by Verheul in the Netherlands on the Regal Mark IV chassis.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] They were interesting buses, faster than Leyland Tiger in use by other fleets.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] It was said at the time (early '60s) that the main reason was inter-urban gearing instead of purely urban gearing present in Leylands.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] An interesting feature was the preselector gear-change, similar to those in Leyland buses, controlled by a small gated lever installed by the steering wheel, with a reversed gate, with first gear to the right and up, and fourth gear to the bottom and left.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] In Argentina, 25 Verheul buses also built on the Regal Mark IV chassis were sold in 1961.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] In Spain, ACLOs could be seen mainly as double-deck buses in Barcelona, and as line coaches in ALSA fleet.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] In Portugal, the AEC vehicles, mainly coaches and buses but also lorries, were assembled and bodied by UTIC, a large coachbuilding firm based in Lisbon and Porto, and were marketed under the UTIC-AEC badge.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] AEC based vehicles were market leaders in Portugal, for instance, by the time of creation of Rodoviária Nacional, in 1975, those accounted for 67.5% of the more than 2500 buses and coaches inherited fleet.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] Production remained strong throughout the late 1970s and would cease in the end of 1980.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] From 1971 to 1973 the Loughborough based dealer Moseley imported nine UTIC U2043 coaches which were marketed as the Moseley Continental Tagus.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] They were mechanically equivalent to a rear-engined Reliance or a coach version of the Swift 691 which AEC had planned but never marketed.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] They were expensive to buy new and the square sided styling looked dated to British eyes in the age of the Elite and Dominant coaches, thus they were slow selling.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] These were probably the only right hand drive coaches built by UTIC.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] At the time Moseley also marketed Salvador Caetano Coaches under its own name.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] In the late 1950s, Spanish government restrictions on imports reduced AEC sales in Spain to virtually nil.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] As a consequence, AEC approached a Spanish truck manufacturer, Barreiros Diesel, to jointly produce buses and coaches based on AEC designs.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The venture started in 1961, used **Barreiros AEC** as brand name, disregarding ACLO, and seemed promising; production of the AEC off-road dump trucks being planned too.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] Nevertheless, the Leyland takeover in 1962 soon undermined the agreement, as Leyland was partnering with Barreiros's Spanish arch-rival, Pegaso.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] Eventually, Barreiros looked for another collaborator in the bus arena, signing in 1967 an agreement with Belgian company Van Hool.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] AEC's first purpose-built commercial vehicle, the Y Type was introduced in 1915.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] More than ten thousand of these vehicles were supplied to the War Department by 1919.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] Many of these were acquired by civilian operators following the war.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] YB and YC Types continued in production until 1921.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The AEC Roadtrain was an experimental early 1930s road train.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The AEC Mammoth was introduced in 1930, being largest truck in the AEC range and the first to be available as a cabover.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] It was originally a 7/8 ton 4x2 lorry with a six-cylinder overhead valve engine developing 110 bhp (82 kW) on a wheelbase of 16 ft 7 in.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] From 1934 a distinction was made between the lighter Mammoth Minor, and the heavier Mammoth Major 6 (6x4) and Mammoth Major 8 (8x2 or 8x4), which appeared in 1934.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The Mammoth Major Mk II was introduced in 1935; the eight-wheeler could carry 15-ton loads.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] It remained in production until 1948 when it was superseded by the Mk III, which was mechanically similar, but had the Park Royal cab.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] Subsequent Mammoth Majors featured the Mk V cab, and finally the tilting Ergomatic cab.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The original 4x2 Mammoth and lightweight Mammoth Minor were relatively short-lived models, but both names were later re-used.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The AEC Mandator name was originally used for medium-duty models in the 1930s, but in 1949 the Matador 4x2 was renamed Mandator.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The name was used for the heavier AEC 4x2s until the end of production in the 1970s, and was especially popular as a tractor unit.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The Leyland Marathon (1973–79) was a high powered 4x2 or 6x4 tractor unit with a modified Ergomatic cab, which was built at the AEC factory in Southall.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] A few were given AEC badges to satisfy individual customer preferences.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The Marathon name had formerly been used on a Maudslay bus chassis.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] Pre-war 6x4 3ton military lorry built with various body styles – some were employed by the Royal Air Force as cranes (using the Coles Crane).
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The name was reintroduced for 6x2 and 6x4 medium-duty lorries from the 1960s–1970s.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The original AEC Matador five-ton 4x2 commercial lorry was introduced in 1932, but the name was most famously used for the 4x4 artillery tractor version introduced in 1938.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] These vehicles exploited AEC's experience with four-wheel drive that it had gained from its involvement in the British Four Wheel Drive vehicles marketed under the name **Hardy**.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] AEC produced 9,620 artillery tractors; 514 6x6 bowsers for the Royal Air Force; 192 6x6 lorries (some of which had Coles Cranes mounted); and 185 similar vehicles, but 6x4, for mobile oxygen plants.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] New civilian Matadors appeared after the war, and many ex-military Matadors were adapted for post-war commercial use, especially as timber lorries and recovery vehicles.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] There was a final short run of the 0853 4x4 Matador for the Army in the early fifties, due to ongoing issues with the introduction of the replacement Leyland.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The last Matador was a 4x4 variant of the Mercury, introduced in 1960.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The Matador name is often used for the 10-ton 6x6 military vehicles of Model 854/O854 (built 1940–44), but this model was never given an official name.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] It was an extended Matador chassis, mated to a Marshal double-drive bogie.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The AEC Mercury (Model 440) was first built in 1928.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] This was a forward-control lorry with a wheelbase of 14 ft (4.3 m) for 4 ton payloads.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The Model 640 was introduced in 1930, with a four-cylinder petrol engine developing 65 bhp.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The name was resurrected for medium-duty 4x2 lorries and tractors built from the 1950s to the 1970s.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The AEC Militant – or "Milly" – was the 1952 replacement for the Matador; a 6x4 or 6x6 artillery tractor/military lorry which continued in various forms until the 1970s.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The Militant name had earlier been used by Maudslay in the 1930s.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The AEC Mogul model GM4 (1959–67) was a normal-control 4x2 built primarily for export markets.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The Mogul name had originally been used on Maudslay lorries.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The original AEC Monarch was built from 1931 to 1939 at AEC's Southall works.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The first version had payload of 7 tons (increased to 7+1⁄2 tons from 1933) and was fitted with either an 85 hp (63 kW) four-cylinder 5.1-litre diesel engine or an 80 hp four-cylinder 5.1-litre petrol engine.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] This was a robust and well-designed lorry, popular with both drivers and operators.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] The model was discontinued in the 1950s, although the name lived on into the 1970s in some export markets.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] 2012 was the centenary of the founding of AEC Ltd, and to mark this, a number of events took place throughout the year.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] By far the biggest was hosted by The AEC Society, and was held over the weekend of 26 and 27 May 2012 at Newark Showground in Nottinghamshire.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] It was the biggest ever gathering of AECs vehicles, and over 225 attended, as well as more than 350 vehicles of other marques.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/aec-associated-equipment-company] It was the biggest rally ever held by The AEC Society and was closed by a flypast by the Battle of Britain memorial flight.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/afa-automobile] The **Aymerich Fábrica de Automoviles** (**AFA**) was a Spanish automobile manufactured between 1943 and 1944.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/afa-automobile] Little is known about the marque other than that a few (1 or 2) 5cv 4-cylinder cabriolets were built by Joan Aymerich Casanoves in Barcelona.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/afa-automobile] The AFA was powered by a four-stroke 527 cc engine that produced 13 hp (9.7 kW) at 3,500 rpm.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/afa-automobile] The AFA microcar had a manual transmission with four gears with a top speed of 85 km/h (53 mph).
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/afa-automobile] The AFA prototype was registered in Barcelona in April 1943, with the registration number B-72.107 and its patent number was 159,882.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/afa-automobile] The company exhibited at the Exposición Automovilista Nacional in Madrid on July 10, 1944.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/afa-automobile] In 2008, a son of Joan Aymerich contacted the mNACTEC, Terrassa, which took the only remaining car and restored it.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/afa-automobile] After three years of restoration work, the AFA is now on exhibition in the Transport collection at mNACTEC.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/afa-automobile] In 1935, Casanoves had created the failed "National Ruby" car, due to the outbreak of the Spanish Civil War he was not able to go to production.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/afa-automobile] But his experience served as the basis for the AFA.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/afa-automobile] Casanoves hoped to make 100 cars annually, but only produced one or two cars.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/afa-automobile] He died in 1946, and the car project was then abandoned in 1947.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] An **ambulance** is a medically equipped vehicle used to transport patients to treatment facilities, such as hospitals.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Typically, out-of-hospital medical care is provided to the patient during the transport.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Ambulances are used to respond to medical emergencies by emergency medical services (EMS), and can rapidly transport paramedics and other first responders, carry equipment for administering emergency care, and transport patients to hospital or other definitive care.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Most ambulances use a design based on vans or pickup trucks, though others take the form of motorcycles, buses, hearses, aircraft and boats.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Ambulances are generally considered emergency vehicles authorized to be equipped with emergency lights and sirens.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Generally, vehicles count as an ambulance if they can transport patients.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] However, it varies by jurisdiction as to whether a non-emergency patient transport vehicle (also called an ambulette) is counted as an ambulance.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] These vehicles are not usually (although there are exceptions) equipped with life-support equipment, and are usually crewed by staff with fewer qualifications than the crew of emergency ambulances.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Conversely, EMS agencies may also have nontransporting EMS vehicles that cannot transport patients.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] The term *ambulance* comes from the Latin word *ambulare* as meaning 'to walk or move about' which is a reference to early medical care where patients were moved by lifting or wheeling.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] The word originally meant a moving hospital, which follows an army in its movements.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Ambulances (*ambulancias* in Spanish) were first used for emergency transport in 1487 by the Spanish forces during the siege of Málaga by the Catholic Monarchs against the Emirate of Granada.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] During the American Civil War vehicles for conveying the wounded off the field of battle were called ambulance wagons.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Field hospitals were still called ambulances during the Franco-Prussian War of 1870 and in the Serbo-Turkish war of 1876 even though the wagons were first referred to as ambulances about 1854 during the Crimean War.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] The history of the ambulance begins in ancient times, with the use of carts to transport incurable patients by force.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Ambulances were first used for emergency transport in 1487 by the Spanish, and civilian variants were put into operation during the 1830s.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Advances in technology throughout the 19th and 20th centuries led to modern self-powered ambulances.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Ambulances can be grouped into types depending on whether or not they transport patients, and under what conditions.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Ambulance design must take into account local conditions and infrastructure.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Maintained roads are necessary for road-going ambulances to arrive on scene and then transport the patient to a hospital, though in rugged areas four-wheel drive or all-terrain vehicles can be used.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Fuel must be available and service facilities are necessary to maintain the vehicle.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Methods of summoning (e.g. telephone) and dispatching ambulances usually rely on electronic equipment, which itself often relies on an intact power grid.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Ambulances often have two stages of manufacturing.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] The first is frequently the manufacture of light or medium truck chassis-cabs or full-size vans (or in some places, cars) such as Mercedes-Benz, Nissan, Toyota, or Ford.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] The second manufacturer (known as second stage manufacturer) modifies the vehicle (which is sometimes purchased incomplete, having no body or interior behind the driver's seat) and turns it into an ambulance by adding bodywork, emergency vehicle equipment, and interior fittings.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] This is done by one of two methods – either coachbuilding, where the modifications are started from scratch and built on to the vehicle, or using a modular system, where a pre-built 'box' is put on to the empty chassis of the ambulance, and then finished off.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Modern ambulances are typically powered by internal combustion engines, which can be powered by any conventional fuel, including diesel, gasoline or liquefied petroleum gas, depending on the preference of the operator and the availability of different options.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] As electric vehicles become more common ambulances are moving to electricity and can even be solar-powered with solar photovoltaic modules integrated into the rooftops.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Colder regions often use gasoline-powered engines, as diesels can be difficult to start when they are cold.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Warmer regions may favor diesel engines, as they are more efficient and more durable.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Diesel power is sometimes chosen due to safety concerns, after a series of fires involving gasoline-powered ambulances during the 1980s.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] These fires were ultimately attributed in part to gasoline's higher volatility in comparison to diesel fuel.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] The type of engine may be determined by the manufacturer: in the past two decades, Ford would only sell vehicles for ambulance conversion if they are diesel-powered.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Beginning in 2010, Ford will sell its ambulance chassis with a gasoline engine in order to meet emissions requirements.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] In the United Kingdom, the National Health Service has set a target for all ambulances to be fully electric as part of the Net Zero campaign by 2045.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Many regions have prescribed standards which ambulances should, or must, meet in order to be used for their role.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] These standards may have different levels which reflect the type of patient which the ambulance is expected to transport (for instance specifying a different standard for routine patient transport than high dependency), or may base standards on the size of vehicle.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] For instance, in Europe, the European Committee for Standardization publishes the standard CEN 1789, which specifies minimum compliance levels across the build of ambulance, including crash resistance, equipment levels, and exterior marking.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] In the United States, standards for ambulance design have existed since 1976, where the standard is published by the General Services Administration and known as KKK-A-1822.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] This standard has been revised several times, and is currently in version 'F' change notice #13, known as KKK-A-1822F.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] The National Fire Protection Association has also published a design standard, NFPA 1917, which offers an alternative to KKK-A-1822F.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] The Commission on Accreditation of Ambulance Services (CAAS) has published its Ground Vehicle Standard for Ambulances v2.0, effective July 2019.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] This standard is similar to the KKK-A-1822F and NFPA 1917–2019 specifications.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] The decision on which of the current (3) standards to require is left up to each individual state legislature or EMS director.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Some states have no specific requirement, while others specify which standard is acceptable.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Others, yet, allow the end user to decide which standard to comply to.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] In the United States and Canada, there are four types of ambulances: Type I, Type II, Type III, and Type IV.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Type I is based on a heavy truck chassis-cab with a custom rear compartment that is often referred to as a "box" or "module", primarily used for Advanced Life Support (ALS) or Mobile Intensive Care Unit (MICU), as well as rescue work.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Type II is based on a commercial heavy-duty van with few modifications except for a raised roof and a secondary air conditioning unit for the rear of the vehicle, primarily used for Basic Life Support (BLS) and transfer of patients, though they are occasionally also used for ALS and rescue.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Type III is a van chassis-cab with a custom-made rear compartment, used for ALS and rescue.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Type IV is for *ad hoc* patient transfer using smaller utility vehicles selected for maneuverability in special environments such as dense crowds at events; these are uncommon and are not subject to federal regulations in the United States.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] The move towards standardisation is now reaching countries without a history of prescriptive codes, such as India, which approved its first national standard for ambulance construction in 2013.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Ambulances, like other emergency vehicles, are required to operate in most weather conditions, including those during which civilian drivers often elect to stay off the road.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Also, the ambulance crew's responsibilities to their patient often preclude their use of safety devices such as seat belts.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Research has shown that ambulances are more likely to be involved in motor vehicle collisions resulting in injury or death than either fire trucks or police cars.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Unrestrained occupants, particularly those riding in the patient-care compartment, are particularly vulnerable.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] When compared to civilian vehicles of similar size, one study found that on a per-accident basis, ambulance collisions tend to involve more people, and result in more injuries.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] An 11-year retrospective study concluded in 2001 found that although most fatal ambulance crashes in the United States occurred during emergency runs, they typically occurred on improved, straight, dry roads, during clear weather.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Furthermore, paramedics are also at risk in ambulances while helping patients, as 27 paramedics died during ambulance trips in the US between 1991 and 2006.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] In addition to the equipment directly used for the treatment of patients, ambulances may be fitted with a range of additional equipment which is used in order to facilitate patient care.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] In parts of the world that lack a high level of infrastructure, ambulances are designed to meet local conditions, being built using intermediate technology.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Ambulances can also be trailers, which are pulled by bicycles, motorcycles, tractors, or animals.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Animal-powered ambulances can be particularly useful in regions that are subject to flooding.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Motorcycles fitted with sidecars (or motorcycle ambulances) are also used, though they are subject to some of the same limitations as more traditional over-the-road ambulances.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] The level of care provided by these ambulances varies between merely providing transport to a medical clinic to providing on-scene and continuing care during transport.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] The design of intermediate technology ambulances must take into account not only the operation and maintenance of the ambulance, but its construction as well.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] The robustness of the design becomes more important, as does the nature of the skills required to properly operate the vehicle.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Cost-effectiveness can be a high priority.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Emergency ambulances are highly likely to be involved in hazardous situations, including incidents such as a road traffic collision, as these emergencies create people who are likely to be in need of treatment.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] They are required to gain access to patients as quickly as possible, and in many countries, are given dispensation from obeying certain traffic laws.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] For instance, they may be able to run the red light or stop sign , or be permitted to break the speed limit.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Generally, the priority of the response to the call will be assigned by the dispatcher, but the priority of the return will be decided by the ambulance crew based on the severity of the patient's illness or injury.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Passive visual warnings are usually part of the design of the vehicle, and involve the use of high contrast patterns.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Older ambulances (and those in developing countries) are more likely to have their pattern painted on, whereas modern ambulances generally carry retro-reflective designs, which reflects light from car headlights or torches.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] In addition to retro-reflective markings, some services now have the vehicles painted in a bright (sometimes fluorescent) yellow or orange for maximum visual impact, though classic white or red are also common.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Fire department-operated ambulances are often painted red to match the fire apparatuses.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Another passive marking form is the word *ambulance* (or local language variant) spelled out in reverse on the front of the vehicle.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] This enables drivers of other vehicles to more easily identify an approaching ambulance in their rear view mirrors.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Ambulances may display the name of their owner or operator, and an emergency telephone number for the ambulance service.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Ambulances may also carry an emblem (either as part of the passive warning markings or not), such as a Red Cross, Red Crescent or Red Crystal (collective known as the Protective Symbols).
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] These are symbols laid down by the Geneva Convention, and all countries signatory to it agree to restrict their use to either (1) Military Ambulances or (2) the national Red Cross or Red Crescent society.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Use by any other person, organization or agency is in breach of international law.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] The protective symbols are designed to indicate to all people (especially combatants in the case of war) that the vehicle is neutral and is not to be fired upon, hence giving protection to the medics and their casualties, although this has not always been adhered to.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] In Israel, Magen David Adom, the Red Cross member organization use a red Star of David, but this does not have recognition beyond Israeli borders, where they must use the Red Crystal.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] The Star of Life is widely used, and was originally designed and governed by the U.S.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, because the Red Cross symbol is legally protected by both National and international law.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Ambulance services with historical origins such as the Order of St John, the Order of Malta Ambulance Corps and Malteser International often use the Maltese cross to identify their ambulances.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] This is especially important in countries such as Australia, where St.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] John Ambulance operate one state and one territory ambulance service, and all of Australia's other ambulance services use variations on a red Maltese cross.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Fire service operated ambulances may display the Cross of St.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Florian (often incorrectly called a Maltese cross) as this cross is frequently used as a fire department logo (St.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Florian being the patron saint of firefighters).
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] The active visual warnings are usually in the form of flashing lights.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] These flash in order to attract the attention of other road users as the ambulance approaches, or to provide warning to motorists approaching a stopped ambulance in a dangerous position on the road.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Common colours for ambulance warning beacons are blue, red, amber, and white (clear).
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] However the colours may vary by country and sometimes by operator.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] There are several technologies in use to achieve the flashing effect.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] These include flashing a light bulb or LED, flashing or rotating halogen, and strobe lights, which are usually brighter than incandescent lights.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Incandescent and LED lights may also be programmed to burn steadily, without flashing, which is required in some provinces.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] These hidden lights may not be apparent until they are activated.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Additionally, some of the standard lights fitted to an ambulance (e.g. headlamps, tail lamps) may be programmed to flash.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Flashing headlights (typically the high beams, flashed alternately) are known as a wig-wag.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Additional white lights may be placed strategically around the vehicle to illuminate the area around it when it is dark, almost always at the rear for loading and unloading stretchers and often at the sides as well.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] In areas very far North or South where there are times of year with long periods of darkness, additional driving lights at the front are often fitted as well to increase visibility for the driver.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] In order to increase safety, it is best practice to have 360° coverage with the active warnings, improving the chance of the vehicle being seen from all sides.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] In some countries, such as the United States, this may be mandatory.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] The roof, front grille, sides and rear of the body, and front fenders are common places to mount emergency lights.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] A certain balance must be made when deciding on the number and location of lights: too few and the ambulance may not be noticed easily, too many and it becomes a massive distraction for other road users more than it is already, increasing the risk of local accidents.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] In addition to visual warnings, ambulances can be fitted with **audible warnings**, sometimes known as sirens, which can alert people and vehicles to the presence of an ambulance before they can be seen.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] The first audible warnings were mechanical bells, mounted to either the front or roof of the ambulance.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Most modern ambulances are now fitted with electronic sirens, producing a range of different noises which ambulance operators can use to attract more attention to themselves, particularly when proceeding through an intersection or in heavy traffic.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] The speakers for modern sirens can be integral to the lightbar, or they may be hidden in or flush to the grill to reduce noise inside the ambulance that may interfere with patient care and radio communications.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Ambulances can additionally be fitted with airhorn audible warnings to augment the effectiveness of the siren system, or may be fitted with extremely loud two-tone air horns as their primary siren.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] A recent development is the use of the RDS system of car radios.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] The ambulance is fitted with a short range FM transmitter, set to RDS code 31, which interrupts the radio of all cars within range, in the manner of a traffic broadcast, but in such a way that the user of the receiving radio is unable to opt-out of the message (as with traffic broadcasts).
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] This feature is built into every RDS radio for use in national emergency broadcast systems, but short-range units on emergency vehicles can prove an effective means of alerting traffic to their presence.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] It is, however, unlikely that this system could replace audible warnings, as it is unable to alert pedestrians, those not using a compatible radio or even have it turned off.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] In the United States, the cost of an ambulance ride may be paid for from several sources, and this will depend on the local situation type of service being provided, by whom, and to whom.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] There are differing levels of qualification that the ambulance crew may hold, from holding no formal qualification to having a fully qualified doctor on board.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Most ambulance services require at least two crew members to be on every ambulance (one to drive, and one to attend the patient).
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] It may be the case that only the attendant need be qualified, and the driver might have no medical training.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] In some locations, an advanced life support ambulance may be crewed by one paramedic and one technician, or in countries like Australia advanced life support registered paramedics.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Military ambulances have historically included vehicles based on civilian designs and at times also included armored, but unarmed, vehicle ambulances based upon armoured personnel carriers (APCs).
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] In the Second World War vehicles such as the Hanomag Sd Kfz 251 half-track were pressed into service as ad hoc ambulances, and in more recent times purpose-built AFVs such as the U.S.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] M1133 medical evacuation vehicle serve the exclusive purpose of armored medical vehicles.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Civilian based designs may be painted in appropriate colors, depending on the operational requirements (i.e. camouflage for field use, white for United Nations peacekeeping, etc.).
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] For example, the British Royal Army Medical Corps has a fleet of white ambulances, based on production trucks.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Military helicopters have also served both as ad hoc and purpose-built air ambulances since they are extremely useful for MEDEVAC.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] In terms of equipment, military ambulances are barebones, often being nothing more than a box on wheels with racks to place manual stretchers, though for the operational conditions and level of care involved this is usually sufficient.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Since laws of war demand ambulances be marked with one of the emblems of the Red Cross not to mount offensive weapons, military ambulances are often unarmed.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] It is a generally accepted practice in most countries to classify the personnel attached to military vehicles marked as ambulances as non-combatants; however, this does not always exempt medical personnel from coming under fire – accidental or deliberate.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] As a result, medics and other medical personnel attached to military ambulances are usually put through basic military training, on the assumption that they may have to use a weapon.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] The laws of war do allow non-combatant military personnel to carry individual weapons for protecting themselves and casualties.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] However, not all militaries exercise this right to their personnel.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] The Israeli Defense Forces modified a number of its Merkava main battle tanks with ambulance features in order to allow rescue operations to take place under heavy fire in urban warfare.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] The modifications were made following a failed rescue attempt in which Palestinian gunmen killed two soldiers who were providing aid for a Palestinian woman in Rafah.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Since M113 armored personnel carriers and regular up-armored ambulances are not sufficiently protected against anti-tank weapons and improvised explosive devices, it was decided to use the heavily armored Merkava tank.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Its rear door enables the evacuation of critically wounded soldiers.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Israel did not remove the Merkava's weaponry, claiming that weapons were more effective protection than emblems since Palestinian militants would disregard any symbols of protection and fire at ambulances anyway.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Some navies operate ocean-going hospital ships to lend medical assistance in high casualty situations such as wars or natural disasters.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] These hospital ships fulfill the criteria of an ambulance (transporting the sick or injured), although the capabilities of a hospital ship are more on par with a Mobile Army Surgical Hospital.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] In line with the laws of war, these ships can display a prominent Red Cross or Red Crescent to confer protection under the appropriate Geneva Convention.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] However, this designation has not always protected hospital ships from enemy fire.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Ambulettes provide patient transport service for non-emergency situations.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Scheduling is a major factor in their effective use.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] When an ambulance is retired, it may be donated or sold to another EMS provider or find their new usage in developing countries.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Alternately, it may be adapted into a storage and transport vehicle for crime scene identification equipment, a command post at community events, or support vehicle, such as a logistics unit.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Others are refurbished and resold, or may just have their emergency equipment removed to be sold to private businesses or individuals, who then can use them as small recreational vehicles.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] They may also have a perfectly serviceable body or vehicle (or both) separated from the other and reused.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Toronto City Council operates a "Caravan of Hope" project to give retired Toronto ambulances a second life by donating them to the people of El Salvador.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/ambulance] Since Ontario laws require ambulances to be retired after just four and a half years in service, the City of Toronto decommissions and auctions around 28 ambulances each year.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/america-spanish-automobile] The **America** was a Spanish automobile manufactured in Barcelona from 1917 to 1922.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/america-spanish-automobile] The four-cylinder "valveless" model, the "Tipo A", had a primitive synchromesh gearbox and worm final drive.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/america-spanish-automobile] The firm's main product was the 1097cc "Tipo B"; the "Tipo C" was an ohv racing model.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/america-spanish-automobile] The general director and technical director of América Autos was engineer Manuel Pazos.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/america-spanish-automobile] One of his early designs was an elastic wheel intended to replace the inner tube tire, though the invention did not gain much acceptance due to technical issues.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/america-spanish-automobile] In 1917, the company introduced its first model under the "América" brand, the Tipo A, equipped with a four-cylinder engine.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/america-spanish-automobile] The model featured several innovations, including the aforementioned distribution system, a proprietary synchronized carburetor and gearbox (the first built in Spain), a pressurized lubrication system, and an original patented leaf spring and suspension system.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/america-spanish-automobile] The elastic wheel was offered as an option (the car came with conventional wheels as standard).
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/america-spanish-automobile] Despite these innovations, the Tipo A was not commercially successful.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/america-spanish-automobile] The failure of the Tipo A forced the company to reconsider its business strategy, and in 1919 it introduced the Tipo B, a small conventional car with a body designed by industrial coachbuilder Alfons Lucas, who had workshops at 345 Còrsega Street in Barcelona.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/america-spanish-automobile] The Tipo B was presented at the 1919 Barcelona Auto Show, where it received a favorable reception.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/america-spanish-automobile] In 1921, the Tipo C was introduced, based on the B and intended for competition, but only one unit was ever produced.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/america-spanish-automobile] The bodywork was also crafted by Alfons Lucas.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/america-spanish-automobile] Finally, in 1922, the factory closed its doors.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] The company was founded in 1954 as "Barreiros Diesel S.A." by Eduardo Barreiros and based in Madrid.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] Additionally a pay-in-kind contract with Polish Star was active in the late 1950s, by which engineless Star chassis-cab trucks were exported to Spain, while Barreiros engines were sent to Poland; the whole resulted in Barreiros-engined Star tractors being sold in China (and Polish trucks in Spain).
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] Later on Barreiros branched out into the production of passenger cars by means of cooperation (and capital links) with the Chrysler Corporation.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] An agreement was reached with Chrysler in 1963 to build the Dodge Dart, allowing the company to enter the car market.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] Sold as the Barreiros Dart, it had modified front styling, a four-speed gearbox, and all-around disc brakes.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] During that time, the Spanish automobile market was strongly protected, making entering it effectively only possible by domestic manufacturing.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] As the 1960s progressed, the range was extended with some smaller models from Chrysler's French subsidiary, Simca.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] The Barreiros-made Simca 1000 was launched in 1966, and later the Simca 1200 joined the range (in fact the French Simca 1100, but with a bigger standard engine for the Spanish market).
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] A total of 17,589 units were manufactured of both models in Spain, they were produced as a knock-down kit imported from Argentina due to the protectionist Spanish regulations of those years.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] The Dart and the 3700 were the largest national production cars available in Spain during all production years.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] It was an expensive luxury car with very low fuel economy by Spanish standards.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] The GL designation was a luxury model, while the GT was the sportier version.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] All gasoline Dodges had the biggest engine ever mounted into a mass-production car in Spain, the 225 cu in (3.7 L) Chrysler Slant 6 engine.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] The "3700" number is a reference to the 3.7 litres of displacement.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] No other six-cylinder engine car has been produced in numbers as numerous in Spain.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] A diesel Dart (named "Barreiros Diesel") was also produced.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] These models were very basic and very slow, and used the round tail lights from the first-generation Simca 1000.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] A station wagon version, as well as other variants (diplomatic motorcade cars, ambulances, hearses, etc.) were produced.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] Production of the Spanish Dodge Dart/Dodge 3700 stopped in 1977.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] Peugeot bought the Villaverde factory, as Chrysler was divesting European operations in Spain, France, and the United Kingdom.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] Spanish Dodges were popular with members of the Franco government during the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] Admiral Luis Carrero Blanco was killed on 20 December 1973 while travelling in his Dodge 3700 GT.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] On 12 June 1975, Fernando Herrero Tejedor, a Minister Secretary General of the Movimiento Nacional and the politician mentoring Adolfo Suárez, died in a car accident while travelling in his official Dodge 3700 in the municipality of Adanero.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] After the last ten Ghia-built Crown Imperial limousines were completed for Chrysler, Ghia sold its tooling to Barreiros.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] Barreiros built ten limousines, much like those built by Ghia, and similar to the last ten built by Ghia, built as 1965 models with 1966 exterior styling.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] In 1969, Chrysler Europe took complete control of the company.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] In 1975, Barreiros became for the first time the sole source for a Chrysler Europe model when the production lines of the slow-selling Chrysler 180 series were moved to Madrid from Simca's factory in Poissy.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] Unlike in most other European countries, the Chrysler 180 became relatively popular in Spain.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] Barreiros also continued to assemble other Chrysler Europe models for the domestic market, including Simca 1307 (renamed Chrysler 150 in Spain to be more in line with the popular 180) and Simca Horizon.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] On the truck and bus side, a full range of light, medium and heavy models was offered, still marketed as Barreiros in Spain and as Dodge or Fargo elsewhere, but eventually the Dodge badge prevailed in all markets.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] In 1978, Chrysler Europe was sold to PSA, which subsequently renamed all former Chrysler/Simca models Talbot (so, for example, the Chrysler 150 became Talbot 150).
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] Barreiros continued to assemble Talbot car models launched under the PSA reign, such as Talbot Solara or Talbot Samba.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] The truck and bus division was sold to Renault, also called RVI, and for a short time, the former original Barreiros models, mostly of them trucks, were sold badged as Renaults / Spanish Renault.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] The Barreiros Diesel SA motorvehicle factory at Villaverde in Madrid is now owned by the huge "Renault Trucks (Espana) SA" company where modern Renault trucks and heavy vehicles are produced.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] Spanish Prime Minister Admiral Luis Carrero Blanco, who served under Generalísimo Francisco Franco, was assassinated in 1973 while riding in an armoured Dodge 3700 GT by an 80 kg bomb planted by the Basque separatist group ETA.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] The car, whose armoured structure resisted the 80 kg dynamite bomb, was blown over the roof of a building, landing in the building's inner courtyard.
[src:barreiros-manufacturer/barreiros-manufacturer] The car is now on display at the Army Museum of Toledo.
